          <h2 class="no-margins">
            How do I locate an Assistive Listening System?
          </h2>
          <div class="spacer-sm"></div>
          <div class="section-divider home-c-numbers"></div>

          <h5>
            Assistive listening technologies play a crucial role in enabling
            people with hearing loss to participate fully in public life.
            However, the presence of such systems is only beneficial if users
            know they are available. That’s where clear, consistent assistive
            listening signage becomes vital.
          </h5>

          <h5>
            Because assistive listening technologies transmit audio signals that
            are invisible and inaudible without the proper receiver, signage is
            the key visual indicator that accessible audio services are
            available. Without clear signs, many people with hearing loss may
            remain unaware of the support available, missing out on improved
            hearing experiences.
          </h5>

          <h5>
            Moreover, clear signage is often a legal requirement under
            accessibility laws worldwide, including the Americans with
            Disabilities Act (ADA) in the United States, the Equality Act in the
            UK, and similar legislation in Europe and Australia. These laws
            mandate that facilities inform visitors of the availability of
            assistive listening devices through properly displayed symbols.
          </h5>
        </div>
